snippet.textDisplay:
These fires in Australia are not caused by climate change.
In the last 200 years , temperatures have only risen by 2 degrees in Australia , which as barely enough to be noticed , and far from being a cause of fires.
When you look back over the years , every 5 years there is a large fire season in Australia , and NOW , its time.
One cause of fires in Oz , is the habits of humans who create high fire risk areas around their homes.
Also , due to a lack of proper land management of forest areas , fuel that feeds fire is kept at high levels.
The sad fact is that it is cheaper for a government to contribute to rebuild burnt out towns , than to maintain areas so fires don't start in the first place.

While climate change is real , the biggest factor which contributes to fires is the human variable.

snippet.textDisplay: ScoMo has made some bad choices PR wise, but what he's actually done isn't that bad (not saying he couldn't be doing a lot more still). He's not wrong in saying firefighting isn't a federal issue, its a state issue. They can't do much until the states request their help, which once they did, they mobilised the army to assist with logistics and evacuations etc. Saying not paying firefighters isn't a priority is because they are VOLUNTEER firefighters, and paying them compromises that. The system they've set up that compensates firefighters that have lost income is a perfect way of keeping that integrity. Paying these volunteers wouldn't really be feasible either. Between two of the worst hit states (Victoria and New South Wales) there are over 100,000 volunteer firefighters. There's no way they could all be paid. I know many of these firefighters and they don't want to be paid. What they do want, and DESERVE, is adequate funding from their respective governments, which isn't currently meeting expectations. Hopefully we get some progress on this front and this publicity assists in moving it along. Thank you to all those that have helped from overseas

snippet.textDisplay:
I'm so happy you have done this. I've been waiting for ages. I'm a Deputy Captain with the NSW Rural Fire Service in Australia and have been fighting these fires since the start of our fire season in July.

We have lost homes and 2 life's in our district in Northern NSW. Sadly we have lost 3 amazing brothers to the fires, wish you mentioned them, true blue heros. They deserve all the prays in the world.

Heading down south to assist on Monday.

Thank you for sending your Firefighters over here honestly you guys have no idea how much it helps us. We are exhausted, tired, emotionally and physically drained and with no stop in sight so every tiny bit of effort helps.
